			<p>I am a student at the <a href="http://www.umass.edu/">University of Massachusetts Amherst</a>. I am a senior, majoring in <a href="http://www.cs.umass.edu/">computer science</a> and <a href="http://www.math.umass.edu/"> mathematics</a>. I come from <a href="http://www.town.dartmouth.ma.us/pages/index">Dartmouth</a>, which is located in south-eastern Massachusetts. I recently finished my last season with the <a href="http://www.umassdrumline.org/"> UMass drumline</a>, in which I played snare drum.</p>

			<p>I am interested in studying computational neuroscience, machine learning, computational complexity, and where they intersect. Last summer, I interned as a software developer with <a href="http://www.epsilon.com/">Epsilon Data Management</a>. This past fall, I worked with professor David Barrington on an independent study project on circuit complexity theory, in which we attempted to describe the computational power of small Boolean circuits with composite number counting gates. Our project culminated with this (unpublished) <a href="investigating-power-circuits.pdf">paper</a>. This past spring, I worked on an independent study project jointly with professors David Barrington and Hava Siegelmann, in which we are studying claims on the abilities of the <a href="http://arxiv.org/pdf/1211.4487v2.pdf">mem-computing model</a>. I am spending the summer working in the <a href="binds.cs.umass.edu">BINDS lab</a>, where I am using machine learning methods to solve problems, helping to design an ERP-based brain-computer interface, and reading / writing about the computational complexity of dynamical systems algorithms. Finally, I am also employed as a lab technician / programmer by the <a href="http://cognaclab.com/wp/"> COGNAC lab</a>, in the department of <a href="http://www.psych.umass.edu/index.php">Cognitive and Brain Sciences</a> at UMass, where I am responsible for writing software and scripts, fixing and purchasing lab equipment, and a bizarre collection of other small tasks.</p>
